SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: St Norbert College has an art collection used for public exhibition and scholarly research.
The income of the funds may be distributed for such educational purposes consistent with the mission and heritage of the College, tax-exempt status and the College's Articles of Incorporation.

St Norbert College Inc is exempt from federal income taxes under Section 501 (c)(3) of the Internal Revenue Code. However, income from certain activities not directly related to the College's tax-exempt purpose is subject to taxation on unrelated business income. In addition, the College qualifies for the charitable contribution deduction under Section 170 (b)(1)(A) and has been classified as an organization other than a private foundation under Section 509(a)(2). The College is also exempt from Wisconsin income taxes. Penalties and interest assessed by income taxing authorities are included in institutional support expenses, if applicable. The College had no interest and penalties related to income taxes for the year ended May 31, 2018. The College's federal returns are subject to examination generally for three years after they are filed and its state returns are subject to examination generally for four years after they are filed.
SNC does not use newspapers or broadcast media to publicize its racially nondiscriminatory policy. The organization does state it on the web and in printed brochures.
The institution received various financial aid and assistance from government agencies. A schedule of expenditures of Federal Awards is available upon request.

To ensure our grants and scholarships are used for proper purpose the Financial Aid Office performs regular maintenance and reconciliation with our Bursar's Office monitoring that all funds awarded to a particular student are being properly credited to their student account. Any changes or adjustments to original award that affect grant and scholarship funding are documented, saved and then copied to our Bursar's Office. These processes are completed utilizing an automated software system which allows us to generate reports at anytime for monitoring and reconciliation purposes. Additionally, we have a yearly audit performed by an outside accounting firm guaranteeing we are staying in compliance with all federal, state, and institutional policies and procedures as well as assuring funding is being used as intended.

For the convenience of the college, Mr Bruess accepted a personal residence within the proximity of the college as a condition of his employment. Also, Mr. Bruess and Mr. Lamm have been provided memberships at local country clubs, which are considered working condition fringe benefits and proper substantiation to the college exists. These items are used for business/entertainment on behalf of the college. Nothing has been included as taxable income. Also, the college paid for President Brian Bruess spouse's travel expenses to attend various college functions. Finally, the college paid the registration fees for Mr. Frick's spouse to attend the CIC Presidential Vocation and Institutions Mission Program in the past year. These costs have not been included as taxable compensation, as the spouses had bona fide business purposes for being on the trips in accordance with IRS Reg 1.132-5(t).
Payment agreement included in up front negotiated contract as approved by the Board of Trustees.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Section B, Line 12c
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: The organization regularly and consistently monitors and enforces compliance with the policy. Exempt (salaried) employees and faculty must complete a "Conflict Disclosure Statement" at the time of hire and in September of each year thereafter and return the statements to the Vice President of Business and Finance. The director of finance and the director of human resources review all statements to determine whether the relationship or transaction is inappropriate. If a relationship or transaction appears to have potential for a conflict of interest, the Vice President of Business and Finance will also review the statement. The reviewing group informs the employee of whether the transaction or relationship will be permitted and under what circumstances. Related to trustees, by-laws require them to disclose any potential conflicts. Every trustee is required to complete a "Conflict Disclosure Statement" upon their assignment to the board. This submission is being reviewed for conflict by a member of the board of trustees. The current members are expected to inform of any changes that lead to potential conflicts.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Section B, Line 15
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: Using CUPA data for comparable organizations as a guide, the compensation for the president is determined by the compensation committee of the Board of Trustees of the college, consisting of the Chairman of the Board, the Vice Chairman of the Board and the Chairman of the Finance Committee and is approved by the Vice President for Business and Finance. Compensation for the College's officers uses CUPA data as a guide for comparable compensation for comparable positions at similarly situated organization. Final approval must be secured from the President of the College and Vice President for Business and Finance, the College's compensation plan is approved as a part of the budget of governing body (the Finance Committee of the Board of Trustees and by the Order) and compensation calculations are documented and records are retained in Human Resources.
